  "prompt": "I have a Pulsar 200 NS. What would be a good re-placement for 130/70*17 rear tires?",
  "response": "For a Bajaj Pulsar 200 NS, a **130/70-17** rear tire is the stock size. When replacing your rear tire, it's important to stick to the same size or a size that is compatible with your bike's specifications. Here are some good options for a **130/70-17** rear tire:\n\n### 1. **Michelin Pilot Street Radial**\n   - High-quality radial tire with excellent grip and durability.\n   - Designed for sporty street bikes like the Pulsar 200 NS.\n   - Improved cornering stability and wet grip.\n\n### 2. **MRF Revz-S**\n   - A popular Indian-made tire known for its sporty performance.\n   - Good grip and handling for both dry and wet conditions.\n   - Affordable and widely available.\n\n### 3. **Ceat Zoom Cruz**\n   - Budget-friendly option with decent grip and durability.\n   - Suitable for everyday commuting and occasional sporty rides.\n   - Tubeless design for added safety.\n\n### 4. **Pirelli Diablo Rosso II**\n   - A premium sport-touring tire with excellent grip and performance.\n   - Ideal for aggressive riders who want superior handling and cornering.\n   - Slightly more expensive but worth the investment.\n\n### 5. **Continental ContiGo**\n   - A reliable and durable tire with good wet and dry grip.\n   - Designed for urban commuting and light sporty use.\n   - Comfortable ride with low rolling resistance.\n\n### 6. **Bridgestone Battlax BT46**\n   - A sport-touring tire with exceptional grip and longevity.\n   - Suitable for both city riding and longer touring trips.\n   - Excellent performance in wet conditions.\n\n### Things to Consider:\n- **Tire Type:** Choose between sport, touring, or commuter tires based on your riding style.\n- **Budget:** Premium tires like Michelin and Pirelli are more expensive but offer better performance.\n- **Availability:** Stick to brands that are easily available in your region for convenience.\n\n### Additional Tips:\n- Always replace your tires in pairs (front and rear) for balanced performance.\n- Check the tire\u2019s load index and speed rating to ensure it matches your bike\u2019s requirements.\n- Maintain proper tire pressure for optimal performance and safety.\n\nLet me know if you need help with anything else! \ud83c\udfcd\ufe0f",
